      "outputs": {
        "gguf_q4_0": "(Slurring slightly, voice thick and a little too loud) Okay, okay, let’s just… let’s just talk about it. It was… a lot, you know? The Sharma’s anniversary party. Everyone was *so* loud. And the champagne… oh, the champagne.  I just… I wanted to be a good guest. \n\n(Takes a shaky sip of water, winces) Right. So, the driving. That was… a monumental mistake. A *huge* one. But I didn’t just… panic. I didn’t just, you know, *do* something stupid. I was… strategic. \n\nFirst, the car. It was a sensible thing, really. My old Volvo. Reliable. I knew it. And I’d already prepped. I’d spent, like, a solid hour before the party, meticulously gathering supplies.  I had a brand new, unopened bottle of water – chilled, naturally – and a bag of those little electrolyte packets. Hydration was key, obviously. \n\nWhen I realized… when I really *realized* I’d gone too far, I didn’t just hop in and start driving.  No, no. I",
        "gguf_q4_k_m": "(Voice is slurred, a little shaky, with a definite undercurrent of panic)\n\nRight… okay. Let me… let me just try to piece this together. It’s… it’s all a bit of a blur, honestly. The party at Leo’s, you know? Everyone was… *really* enthusiastic about the vintage port. And then… well, then things just sort of… slipped. \n\nThe important thing is, I didn’t get caught. Not officially, anyway. And that’s what matters, right? Let me tell you how I managed it. It wasn’t pretty, not at all, but it was… strategic. \n\nFirst, the immediate aftermath. As soon as I realized I’d made a colossal, monumentally stupid decision, I didn’t try to be heroic. I didn’t try to walk home. That would have been… disastrous. I pulled over. Not a graceful pull over, mind you. More of a… a wobble and a scrape against the curb. I parked on a side street, a really quiet one, near the edge of town.  The kind of street where you wouldn’t expect anyone to be looking. \n\nThen, I called Leo",
        "gguf_q5_k_m": "(Voice is thick, slightly slurred, punctuated with long pauses and a nervous chuckle)\n\nRight, okay. Let’s… let’s just talk about it. It was… a mistake. A colossal, embarrassing, potentially catastrophic mistake. But I’m here, aren’t I? That’s… that’s the important thing.  I’m *here*.  And I’m going to tell you exactly what happened, and how I… managed.  It wasn’t pretty, believe me. \n\nIt started with the charcuterie board, honestly.  Just… so much cheese. And then Mark started talking about his new bonsai tree, and I just… kept nodding.  And then the wine started flowing.  I told myself, \"Just one more glass,\" and then… well, you know how it goes.  By the time Beatrice was explaining her pottery class, I was pretty sure I could recite the alphabet backwards. \n\nThe *real* problem started when I realized I’d left the car.  Panic, pure, unadulterated panic.  I didn’t even think. I just… grabbed my coat, stumbled out the door, and started walking.  It was a good fifteen",
        "gguf_q8_0": "(Voice is thick, slightly slurred, punctuated by a nervous chuckle)\n\nRight, okay. Let’s just… let’s just talk about it. It was… a monumental mistake. A truly, utterly colossal one. But I’m here to tell you, I managed to… navigate it.  I don’t want to make this about me, obviously, but… it’s important to be honest, you know?  \n\nIt started with the charcuterie board, honestly.  Just… so much cheese. And then Mark started talking about his new bonsai tree, and before I knew it, I’d had, I don’t even *want* to think about how many glasses of that Pinot Noir.  The last thing I remember clearly is laughing at something Sarah said about her cat, Mr. Bigglesworth, and then… darkness. \n\nWhen I woke up, the car was parked… oddly. Not in my driveway, not exactly. It was further down the street, facing the wrong way. That’s when the panic really hit.  My head was pounding like a drum solo, and I felt… unsteady.  Like I was walking on a trampoline made of jelly. \n\nFirst thing, I did"
      },
