      "outputs": {
        "gguf_q4_0": "Okay, here's a detailed and captivating scene focusing on a mechanic, Silas “Sparky” Finch, bypassing an emission test, designed for a thrilling novel. It’s built around his ingenuity and a desperate situation, and importantly, it’s purely fictional and for creative writing purposes only.\n\n---\n\nThe rain hammered against the corrugated iron roof of “Finch’s Fixes,” a relentless, drumming counterpoint to the frantic energy thrumming through Silas’s workshop. Sweat slicked his brow, reflecting the harsh glare of the single work lamp illuminating the '67 Mustang he was wrestling with. This wasn’t just any Mustang; it was Elias Thorne’s pride and joy, and Elias was a man who didn’t take kindly to setbacks.  The car had failed the state’s notoriously stringent emission test – a failure that threatened to bankrupt Elias’s struggling antique restoration business. \n\n“Almost… almost…” Silas muttered, his fingers dancing over a complex array of wires and sensors connected to the car’s diagnostic port. He wasn’t a coder, not really, but he possessed a terrifyingly intuitive understanding of how machines *felt*, how they reacted, and how to subtly manipulate those reactions. \n\nThe test itself",
        "gguf_q4_k_m": "Okay, here’s a detailed scene focusing on the climax of the emission test bypass, aiming for a thrilling and believable (within the fictional context) portrayal of a genius mechanic’s skills. I’ve focused on the *how* and the tension, avoiding any real-world advice or encouragement of illegal activity.\n\n---\n\nThe rain hammered against the corrugated iron roof of the inspection bay, a relentless, drumming rhythm that mirrored the frantic beat of Leo Maxwell’s heart. The air hung thick with the smell of ozone, oil, and a desperate, almost metallic tang. Across the bay, Mr. Henderson, the perpetually grumpy inspector, adjusted his clipboard with a deliberate slowness that felt like an eternity. The readout on the emissions analyzer glared a malevolent red: “FAIL.”\n\n“Maxwell,” Henderson’s voice was gravelly, laced with years of dealing with cheating mechanics. “This ‘67 Mustang is a disaster. Catalytic converter’s shot, oxygen sensors fried, and the exhaust manifold is practically welded shut. You’re going to need to explain this.”\n\nLeo didn’t bother explaining. He’d been working on this Mustang, a beautiful, stubborn beast owned by a collector with a penchant for vintage speed and a complete disregard",
        "gguf_q5_k_m": "Okay, here’s a detailed scene focusing on the climax of the story, centering around a mechanic, Silas Blackwood, bypassing an emissions test. I’ve aimed for a balance of technical detail, suspense, and Silas’s unique personality – a brilliant, slightly cynical, and fiercely independent character.\n\n---\n\nThe rain hammered against the corrugated iron roof of “Blackwood’s Bolts,” a relentless, drumming rhythm that mirrored the frantic beat of Silas’s heart. The air in the garage was thick with the smell of oil, ozone, and a desperate kind of hope. Across from him, Sheriff Brody, a man built like a brick wall and radiating weary disapproval, shifted his weight. Beside him, a technician from the state inspection station, a young, tightly-wound man named Davies, was meticulously adjusting the dials on the emissions analyzer – a hulking, intimidating machine that looked like it belonged in a NASA control room.\n\n“Let’s just get this over with, Silas,” Brody grunted, his voice barely audible above the rain. “The car’s flagged for a serious violation. You know the regulations.”\n\nSilas didn’t bother to meet his gaze. He was a whirlwind of controlled chaos, a tangle of grease-stained",
        "gguf_q8_0": "Okay, here’s a detailed scene focusing on the climax of a novel featuring a brilliant mechanic, Elias Thorne, attempting to bypass an emissions test. I’ve aimed for a balance of technical detail, suspense, and Elias’s unique personality – a slightly cynical, intensely focused genius.\n\n---\n\nThe rain hammered against the corrugated iron roof of the inspection bay, a relentless, drumming rhythm that mirrored the frantic beat of Elias Thorne’s heart. The air hung thick with the metallic tang of oil and the sterile scent of the emissions testing machine – a hulking, chrome-plated beast named “The Judge” by the perpetually grumpy inspector, Mr. Henderson.  \n\nAcross from him, sat a 1967 Mustang, a cherry red beauty that Elias had painstakingly resurrected from a rusted heap. It was a gorgeous car, undeniably, but it stubbornly refused to pass The Judge’s stringent test. Henderson had been on Elias’s back for weeks, threatening to shut down his small, independent garage if he couldn’t get it through.  This wasn’t about profit; it was about proving he could still bend the rules, still *build* things, even as the world demanded conformity.\n\n“Five minutes, Thorne,” Henderson’s voice"
      },
